<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,399,1302]" pageId="2" pageNumber="524">
<keyLead pageId="2" pageNumber="524">
– Larger species, distal antennomeres of male (4–10) as long as wide or longer; vertex about 0.6 times as wide as width of eye; pronotum with very fine, medial, lustrous line at posterior half, lateroposterior depressions shallow, wide (
<figureCitation box="[1233,1294,751,774]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="3.[151,212,1858,1882]" captionTargetBox="[251,1343,182,1829]" captionTargetId="figure-24@3.[230,1358,181,1834]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGS. 1–9. Historical types. 1—Anthaxia dispar Kerremans, 1898, holotype, female 7.1 mm; 2—A. hyperlasia Obenberger, 1928, holotype, female, 8.9 mm; 3—A. komareki Obenberger, 1931, holotype, male, 4.8 mm; 4—A. lasioptera Obenberger, 1915, holotype, female, 7.3 mm; 5—A. pilifrons Kerremans, 1898, holotype, male, 7.5 mm; 6—A. vulpes Théry, 1930, holotype, female, 7.2 mm, © MNHN; 7—Anthaxia (Haplathaxia) aethiopica sp. nov., holotype, male, 5.7 mm; 8—A. (H.) caerulea sp. nov., holotype, male, 8.6 mm; 9—A. (H.) dispar Kerremans, 1898, (RSA, Limpopo), male, 7.6 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4408009" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4408009/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="524">Figs 5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1304,1330,751,773]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="6.[151,212,1425,1449]" captionTargetBox="[153,1435,185,1397]" captionTargetId="figure-16@6.[151,1436,181,1400]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGS. 10–15. Habitus.10—A. (H.) dispar, female (RSA, Mpumalanga), 7.7 mm; 11—A. (H.) dispar (RSA, Limpopo), male, lateral view, 7.6 mm; 12—A. (H.) keniae Théry, 1941 (Kenya, Kiserian), male, 5.9 mm; 13—A. (H.) occidentalis sp. nov., holotype, male, 7.8 mm; 14—the same, allotype, female, 7.6 mm; 15—A. (H.) pilifrons Kerremans, 1898, (Zambia, Kafue), female, 7.3 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4408011" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4408011/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="524">15</figureCitation>
); aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[233,303,781,803]" captionStart="FIGS" captionStartId="8.[151,212,1796,1820]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,1174,1771]" captionTargetId="figure-414@8.[151,1436,1173,1773]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGS. 16–22. Aedeagi (not in scale). 16—Anthaxia (Haplathaxia) aethiopica sp. nov., holotype; 17—A. (H.) caerulea sp. nov., holotype; 18—A. (H.) dispar Kerremans, 1898 (RSA, Limpopo); 19—A. (H.) keniae Théry, 1941 (Kenya, Kiserian); 20—A. (H.) komareki Obenberger, 1931, holotype; 21—A. (H.) occidentalis sp. nov., holotype; 22—A. (H.) pilifrons Kerremans, 1898, holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4408013" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4408013/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="524">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
) long, almost parallel-sided at basal two thirds, well-sclerotised; 
<quantity box="[929,1047,781,803]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.949999999999999" metricValueMax="7.8" metricValueMin="6.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="524" unit="mm" value="6.949999999999999" valueMax="7.8" valueMin="6.1">6.1–7.8 mm</quantity>
